  "aspect": "vertical", "theme": "navy", "fps": 30, "crossfade": 0.6, "pace": 1.4,
  "voiceover": "Did the Church invent Jesus as God at the Council of Nicaea? It's a popular myth — helped along by novels — but the history is clear. Belief in Jesus' divinity isn't from AD 325. It's in the earliest layers of the New Testament, decades earlier. Paul, writing in the 50s, takes Old Testament 'Lord' texts that were about God and applies them directly to Jesus. And an early hymn he quotes calls Jesus 'in very nature God' — Philippians 2:6. So what did Nicaea actually do? It didn't vote Jesus into divinity. It gathered to defend the language protecting what Christians already believed and worshipped — against a teaching called Arianism that denied it. The council clarified and confessed an ancient faith. It didn't manufacture a new one. Not invented. Confessed.",
  "source": "answers/did-the-church-invent-jesus-divinity-at-nicaea.html",
